ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the effect of Sb-doped Co nanoparticles on the catalytic activity, four different samples (Co, 1 wt% Sb, 5 wt% Sb, and 10 wt% Sb doped Co–Sb catalysts) were prepared and subjected to NaBH4 hydrolysis (Fig. 6
                        ). This systematic investigation allowed the determination of the optimal concentration of Sb to enhance the catalytic activity of Co-based nanoparticles. Sb, when tested as a stand-alone catalyst, exhibited no catalytic activity. This can be attributed to its inherently low catalytic capacity. However, it was observed that the catalytic activity of Co increased with the doping of Sb at certain ratios. NaBH4 hydrolysis was successfully carried out using Co and Sb doped Co catalysts and the high catalytic activity observed in each sample was directly related to the Co content [55]. In contrast, sodium borohydride hydrolysis was successfully carried out using Co, Co-1 wt.% Sb, Co-5 wt.% Sb, and Co-10 wt% Sb catalysts. Notably, the high catalytic activity observed in each sample was directly proportional to the cobalt content, providing strong evidence that Co nanoparticles serve as the primary active sites for the reaction. The absence of cobalt led to a significant decline in catalytic activity, as observed in the case of pure Sb metal, which exhibited substantially lower performance. The hydrolysis completion times for Co, Co-1 wt.% Sb, Co-5 wt.% Sb, and Co-10 wt% Sb catalysts were approximately 12, 5, 8, and 12 min, respectively. Since all four catalysts successfully generated the target hydrogen volume of approximately 680 ml, they can be considered effective for the reaction. However, the 1 wt% Sb doped Co–Sb catalyst exhibited the highest activity among all tested samples. This superior performance can be attributed to the increased number of active sites facilitated by the optimal Sb doping level. In terms of the synergistic effect between Co and Sb, while 1 wt% Sb addition positively influenced catalytic performance, higher Sb concentrations led to a decline in activity. This reduction was likely due to excessive Sb obstructing the active sites on the Co surface, thereby diminishing the overall synergistic effect. Among the tested catalysts, 10 wt% Sb doped Co–Sb catalyst exhibited the lowest hydrogen generation rate and, consequently, the lowest catalytic activity, requiring a significantly longer time to release the full hydrogen content during the hydrolysis process. Based on these findings, the 1 wt% Sb doped Co–Sb catalyst was identified as the optimal composition, and for subsequent investigations, it was referred to as Co–Sb for simplicity. Further experiments were conducted to determine the optimal conditions for maximizing the activity of the Co–Sb catalyst, with a focus on key parameters such as the NaBH4/NaOH ratio, temperature, and reusability. In these experiments, the catalyst quantity was fixed at 25 mg to ensure consistency. Hydrolysis tests were performed at a solution temperature of 30 °C using NaBH4 concentration of 2.5 wt% and varying NaOH concentrations (0 wt%, 1 wt%, 2.5 wt%, 5 wt%, and 7.5 wt%). The experimental results were subsequently plotted to visualize the catalyst's performance under different conditions, as illustrated in Fig. 7
                        .
